{
  "text": "Stocking density is an important parameter in fish culture, not only because it has strong implications on growth performance, but also because it can affect fish welfare [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] 2005) and has an economical impact. Social interactions could be behind the differences observed in growth efficiency of several fish species. For example, gilt-head sea bream feeding efficiency has been observed to be affected by ration size, with lower rations leading to increased competition, faster swimming speeds and higher densities under the feeder [CITATION_3] . Similarly, common sole reared at different stocking densities between 0.5 and 12 kg m \u2212 2 showed a density-dependent growth performance, with productivity maxima at intermediate densities (7.4 kg m",
